<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Black Sea — strategic chokepoint</h1>
    <p class="lead">Why this basin matters for trade, energy and security.</p>
  </header>

  <main>
    <article class="card">
      <section>
        <h2>What’s the point?</h2>
        <p>
          The Black Sea links grain markets, energy flows and sea lanes across Europe, Asia and MENA.
          Before the full-scale war, <strong>Russia and Ukraine</strong> jointly accounted for roughly
          <strong>34% of global wheat exports</strong>, <strong>17% of corn</strong> and
          <strong>~75% of sunflower oil</strong> (FAO). Shipping disruptions and war-risk insurance premia
          translate rapidly into food prices.
        </p>
        <p class="pill">Source: FAO/FAOSTAT (shares in global exports)</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Trade & food</h2>
        <p>
          In 2022–2023 the <em>Black Sea Grain Initiative</em> enabled shipments of about
          <strong>32.9 million tonnes</strong> (mainly corn and wheat) from Ukrainian ports, helping cool
          price pressure in grain/oilseed markets.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Price channel:</strong> reopening reduced risk premia and improved access for MENA/EU importers.</li>
          <li><strong>Logistics:</strong> short route via UA ports → Bosporus → the Med → destination ports.</li>
          <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> tensions lift <em>war-risk</em> premia and bank requirements (LCs, sanctions clauses).</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://www.ifpri.org/blog/black-sea-grain-initiative-what-it-and-what-did-it-accomplish" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IFPRI — Black Sea Grain Initiative (≈32.9 Mt)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Energy</h2>
        <p>
          The region also hosts energy infrastructure: Turkish fuel/LNG terminals and gas pipelines from Russia to TR/EU.
          <strong>TurkStream</strong> has a nameplate capacity of <strong>31.5 bcm/year</strong> (≈ half to TR, half to EU via BG–RS–HU).
          Against EU gas demand in the hundreds of bcm, that’s a <strong>low-single-digit share</strong>—still critical for
          transit states and regional consumers.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Flows & policy:</strong> the Montreux Convention governs strait traffic; incidents raise risk and costs.</li>
          <li><strong>Substitution:</strong> LNG and TR routes reduce exposure to other corridors.</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://turkstream.info/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TurkStream — official project site (31.5 bcm/y)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="wrap">
        <h2>What it means in practice</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Food prices:</strong> restored sailings eased grain/veg-oil indices; renewed shocks push them up.</li>
          <li><strong>Freight & insurance:</strong> NAVTEX/NOTAM notices and incidents lift <em>war-risk</em> premia and freight.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk pass-through:</strong> shippers/banks/insurers pass risk premia into final prices.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="cols">
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="good">Upside / opportunities</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Higher capacity & predictability of lanes (more stable prices, lower premia).</li>
            <li>Logistics diversification (TR, LNG, alternates) reduces chokepoint exposure.</li>
            <li>Better coordination of trade finance & insurance (smoother supply chains).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="bad">Downside / risks</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Sharp spikes in <em>war-risk</em> premia and freight after incidents; possible port stoppages.</li>
            <li>Eskalation can constrain grain availability → higher food baskets in MENA/EU.</li>
            <li>Straits remain bottlenecks (Bosporus, Dardanelles) → queues and delays.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Sources & further reading</h2>
        <ul class="sources">
